revision.text:
'''Anton Erkoreka''' (1950, [[Biscaya]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]]) is a Basque historian of medicine and an ethnographer.<ref>{{cite book |year=2003 |title=La religiosidad popular: Hermandades, romerías y santuarios (III). León Carlos Alvarez Santaló, María Jesús Buxó Rey, Salvador Rodríguez Becerra (coord) |publisher=Anthropos Editorial |isbn=84-7658-662-0}}</ref> He is director of the [[Basque Museum of the History of Medicine and Science]], located at the [[University of the Basque Country]].<ref>{{cite book |year=1988 |title=Euskal antropologoak, etnologoak eta etnografoak gaur |location=Donostia |publisher=Kriselu |isbn=84-7728-105-X}}</ref> His areas of specialization include the history of diseases, in particular the [[Spanish flu pandemic]],<ref>{{cite journal |pages=81–9 |doi=10.1111/j.1750-2659.2009.00125.x |title=The Spanish influenza pandemic in occidental Europe (1918-1920) and victim age |year=2010 |last1=Erkoreka |first1=Anton |journal=Influenza and Other Respiratory Viruses |volume=4 |issue=2 |pmid=20167048}}</ref> folk medicine, such as the [[evil eye]]<ref>{{cite book |first1=Willem |last1=de Blécourt |first2=Owen |last2=Davies |title=Witchcraft continued: popular magic in modern Europe |year=2004 |page=149 |isbn=978-0-7190-6658-0 |chapter=footnote 67 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=B1BmSW_Z1oEC&pg=PA149 |quote=In addition to the rich material provided by Lisón in ''Brujería'', numerous studies have been carried out that are collected in the biographical references of the work by Antón Erkoreka, ''Begizkoa. Mal de ojo'' (Bilbao, 1995), pp. 38, 153–67.}}</ref> and the study of human populations.

