{{About||the Dutch politician|Elise Boot|the American artist|Elizabeth Boott}}
'''Elizabeth Booth''' (born 1674) was a resident of [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]], [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]], who became one of the accusers during the [[Salem Witch Trials]].<ref>[http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/salem/asal_ch.htm]</ref><ref>[http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/salem/sal_acct.htm]</ref>

==Biography==
At 18, Booth was a member of the “outer circle” of girls who  supposedly afflicted by witchcraft, and she participated in examinations, inquests, and trials.<ref name=Drake2009>Drake, Samuel G. “Annals of Witchcraft in New England”, ''The Salem Witch Trials Reader'', ed. Frances Hill. Da Capo Press. Boston. 2009.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref> Booth lived near John Proctor and his wife [[Elizabeth Proctor]], and most of her court proceedings referenced the Proctors. <ref>Roach, Marilynne K. The Salem Witch Trials: A day by day chronicle of a community under siege. Taylor Trade Publications, 2004.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref>

Booth's testimony helped lead to the hangings of [[John Proctor (Salem witch trials)|John Proctor]] and [[Wilmot Redd]], the pressing to death of [[Giles Corey]], and the imprisonment and death sentence of the pregnant Elizabeth Proctor. In October 1692, she married Jonathon Pease.<ref name=Drake2009/>

