'''John Wroe''' (19 September 1782 – 5 February 1863) was a [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] [[Evangelism|evangelist]] who founded the [[Christian Israelite Church]] in the 1820s after having what he believed were a series of  [[Vision (religion)|visions]].

== Biography ==
Wroe was born in the village of [[East Bowling]], near [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]] to a [[worsted]] manufacturer and farmer, and baptised in the town. After a rather scanty education, he entered his father's business, but later took a farm. He married and brought up a family of seven children.

In 1819 Wroe became ill with a [[fever]] and two doctors who attended him considered his life was in serious danger. Wroe asked for a [[minister of religion|minister]] to come and pray with him. Although his wife sent for four church ministers, each refused his request. Wroe then asked his wife to read a few chapters of the [[Bible]] to him, and after a while, he gradually recovered his bodily health, but his mental distress continued and he "wrestled with God" day and night for some months.{{cn|date=December 2012}}

A short time later, Wroe started having [[Vision (spirituality)|visions]], and often became blind and unable to speak — on one occasion remaining blind for six days. During these periods, Wroe said, many remarkable events were foretold and revealed to him: the [[Holy Spirit|Spirit]] told him to relinquish his worldly employment, so he devoted his life to travelling and preaching, where he gained many followers and persuaded them that he was a messenger of God.{{cn|date=December 2012}}

Wroe, although often persecuted and threatened, travelled throughout [[Europe]] including [[Gibraltar]], [[Spain]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], [[Scotland]], and [[Wales]]. He later travelled to the United States, and [[Australia]].<ref>Official Christian Israelite Website 2008</ref>

He died in [[Melbourne]], Australia, in 1863, aged 81, leaving the church affairs in the hands of his [[trustees]]. The Christian Israelite Church was originally set up in [[Gravesend]], [[Kent]], but its headquarters moved to [[Ashton-under-Lyne]], [[Lancashire]], which the church wanted to turn into a "new Jerusalem". From 1822 to 1831 Ashton-under-Lyne was the church's headquarters. Wroe intended to build a wall around the town with four gateways, and although the wall was never constructed, the four gatehouses were, as was a printing press. Popular opinion in the town turned against Wroe when he was accused of indecent behaviour in 1831, but the charges were dismissed. The Church spread to Australia, where it is still active.<ref>Nevell (1994), p.&nbsp;95.</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.tameside.gov.uk/blueplaque/prophetwroe |title=A Tribute to Prophet Wroe 1782&ndash;1863 |publisher=Tameside.gov.uk |accessdate=2009-07-10}}</ref>

==Cultural depictions==
Wroe’s life was the basis of a novel, ''[[Mr Wroe's Virgins]]'' by [[Jane Rogers]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Jane |last=Rogers |authorlink=Jane Rogers |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7CF51GvYY2QC 
|publisher=Hachette UK |title=Mr Wroe's Virgins |year=2011 |isbn=0-618-06613-6}}</ref> In 1993 [[Jonathan Pryce]] featured as Wroe, alongside [[Kathy Burke]] and [[Minnie Driver]], in a [[BBC]] mini-series adaptation of the novel directed by [[Danny Boyle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0106074/|title=Mr. Wroe's Virgins|publisher=|accessdate=31 March 2018|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>

