{{Infobox person | name = Nathan Nata Spiro | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = 1585 | birth_place = | death_date = July 20, 1633 | death_place = Kraków, Poland | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = Kraków, Poland | nationality = Polish | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Chief Rabbi of Kraków | spouse = | children = | parents = Solomon Spiro | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Nathan Nata<ref>Also spelled '''Note''' ({{lang-yi|{{hebrew|נָטֶע}}}})</ref> Spira''' ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|נתן נטע שפירא}}}}; 1585<ref name="Elior">{{cite web|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Spira_Natan_Note_ben_Shelomoh|title=Spira, Natan Note ben Shelomoh|last=Elior|first=Rachel|publisher=[[YIVO]] (Institute for Jewish Research)|accessdate=26 September 2010}}</ref>&nbsp;–&nbsp;July 20, 1633<ref name="JE" />) was a Polish rabbi and kabbalist.<ref name="Sherwin">{{cite book|last=Sherwin|first=Byron L. |title=Sparks Amidst the Ashes: The Spiritual Legacy of Polish Jewry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P3-xVOCy_68C&pg=PA43&dq=%22nathan+nata+shapiro%22&hl=en&ei=CaOfTOOYAoH88AbK96n0Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22nathan%20nata%20shapiro%22&f=false|year=1997|publisher=Oxford University Press US|isbn=978-0-19-510685-5|pages=43 & 65}}</ref> He had an important role in spreading [[Isaac Luria]]'s teachings throughout Poland.<ref name="Sherwin" /> Spira was the author of the ''[[Megaleh Amukot]]''.<ref name="JE">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=1017&letter=S#3390|title=24. Nathan Nata Spira|last=Kayserling|first=Meyer|author2=Schulim Ochser|work=[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=26 September 2010}}</ref> Spira was a student of [[Meir Lublin]].<ref name="Sherwin" />
Spira descended from a rabbinical family, which traced its lineage as far back to [[Rashi]], the noted 11th-century French commentator.<ref name="Elior" /><ref name="Gelles">{{cite book|last=Gelles|first=Edward|title=An Ancient Lineage: European Roots of a Jewish family : Gelles-Griffel-Wahl-Chajes-Safier-Loew-Taube|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=4bWfTKDfF8L78AbkjqGODQ&ct=result&id=QtNtAAAAMAAJ&dq=israel+halpern+megaleh+amukot&q=spiro#search_anchor|year=2006|publisher=Vallentine Mitchell|isbn=978-0-85303-680-7|page=231}}</ref> He was named after his grandfather Nathan Nata Spira, who was rabbi in [[Hrodna]] and authored of ''Mevo Shearim'' (1575) and ''Imrei shefer'' (1597).<ref name="Elior" /><ref name="JE" /> His father was Solomon Spira.<ref name="JE" />
Spira had seven children, three sons and four daughters.<ref name=" Rafaeli">{{cite book|last= Rafaeli|first=Esther |title=The Modest Genius: Reb Aisel Harif|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvjG-F2Z10gC&pg=PA324&dq=nathan+nata+shapira&hl=en&ei=eZ2fTPKzNsP-8Aaj4vHuDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=nathan%20nata%20shapira&f=false|year=2004|publisher=Devora Publishing|isbn=978-1-932687-04-0|page=324}}</ref> Spira was [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Kraków]], but refused a salary.<ref name="JE" /> He is buried in the Old Jewish cemetery in Kazimierz, Krakow.
