{{Infobox military person |name = Noel Newman Lombard Craig |image = |image_size = |alt = |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1884|11|11|df=yes}} |death_date = {{Death date and age|1968|10|31|1884|11|11|df=yes}} |birth_place = [[Ireland]] |death_place = [[Wicklow, Ireland]] |placeofburial =[[Titusville, Pennsylvania]] |placeofburial_label = |nickname = Bungo |birth_name =Newman Lombard Craig |allegiance = {{flagu|United Kingdom}} |branch = [[Queen's Own Cameron Highlanders]], [[Royal Munster Fusiliers]] |serviceyears = 1906–1924 |rank = [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] |servicenumber = |unit = |commands = |battles = World War I * [[Battle of Messines (1917)]] |awards=[[Distinguished Service Order]], [[Legion of Honour]] & [[Sword of Honour (Sandhurst)|Sword of Honour]] |relations = |laterwork = Military Attaché, British Diplomatic Service }}
'''Noel Newman Lombard Craig''' (1884–1968) was an Irish soldier who served in the [[World War I|First World War]]. He was decorated on several occasions including [[Distinguished Service Order]], [[Legion of Honour]], [[Order of the British Empire]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anonymous|title=The Half-Yearly Army List for the Period Ending 31st December 1939|url=http://www.mocavo.com/The-Half-Yearly-Army-List-for-the-Period-Ending-31st-December-1939-Volume-July-December-1939/985565/948|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> and the [[Sword of Honour (Sandhurst)|Sword of Honour]].<ref name=Dublin>{{cite web|last1=Royal Dublin Fusiliers Association|title=Stories / Colonel Noel Newman Lombard Craig, 1884 – 1968 The Royal Munster Fusiliers|url=http://greatwar.ie/stories/noel-craig/|website=Royal Dublin Fusiliers Association|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>
==Early life== Craig was born in 1884, in [[Ireland]]. He was given the nickname "Bungo" by his older brother, after he put a cat into a toilet as a child. He attended [[Trinity College, Dublin]] to study politics, graduating with a B.A. in 1905.<ref name=Dublin /> He enlisted into the [[Queen's Own Cameron Highlanders|Cameron Highlanders]] in 1906, later transferring to [[Royal Munster Fusiliers|The Royal Munster Fusiliers]].<ref name=Dublin /> During his training Craig was awarded the Sword of Honour for excellence in military training.
== Military and Decorations == Whilst a member of the Royal Munster Fusiliers, Craig served in India until 1913. He fought at the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]. In June 1917, at Wytschaete, he was the only one of a group of officers to survive German shelling.<ref name=Dublin />
During World War II, Craig was a [[Military attaché]] and was posted to [[Norway]], [[Finland]], [[Spain]], and [[Denmark]], with his activities earning him a place on the Nazi blacklist.<ref name=Dublin /> Craig was awarded a number of honours including the Distinguished Service Order (DSO) and becoming a member of the French Legion of Honour.
== Later life == Craig married Marian Eleanor Quinby in 1926, having three daughters, Pamela, Clemency and Rosemary.<ref name=Burke>{{cite book|last1=Montgomery-Massingberd|first1=Hugh|title=Burke's Irish Family Records|date=1976|publisher=Burkes Peerage Ltd|location=London|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Craig retired from the British diplomatic service in 1954, returning to [[London]] to practice law at King’s Inn. He was also a published author, writing several novels and over fifty short stories,<ref name=Dublin /> including ''Gulfs'' (1932).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Forgotten Books|title=pp. 59–60|url=http://www.forgottenbooks.com/readbook_text/Catalogue_1000738222/59|website=Forgotten Books|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> Quinby was a native of [[Titusville, Pennsylvania]], with Craig appearing to retire there later in life.<ref name=Burke /><ref name=Titusville>{{cite news|last1=Anonymous|title=Marian Craig Succumbs in Switzerland|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/us/pennsylvania/titusville/titusville-herald/1975/08-23/page-2|accessdate=12 December 2014|agency=Titusville Herald|date=23 August 1975}}</ref>
