A '''Persian name''' consists of a [[given name]], sometimes more than one, and a [[surname]].

==Given names==
{{see also|Category:Persian masculine given names|Category:Persian feminine given names|Category:Iranian masculine given names|Category:Iranian feminine given names}}
Since the [[Islamic conquest of Persia]], some names in Iran have been derived from [[Arabic language|Arabic]] although the majority are Persian in origin. Persian Christians have Arabic names indistinguishable from their [[Muslim]] neighbors. They can also use Arabic derivations of Christian names (such as saints' names), or [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Neo-Aramaic languages|Assyrian]], or [[Armenian language|Armenian]] names, as most Christian Iranians are [[Armenian Iranians]].

Many Persian names come from the great Persian literature book, ''[[Shahnameh]]'' (The Epic of Kings).  It was composed in the 10th century by [[Ferdowsi]] and is considered by many the masterpiece of Persian literature.
Approximately 10%-15% of all Persian names are from Shahnameh. A few examples are Abtin, Ardeshir, Armeen, Arzhang, Babak (Papak), Bijan, Bizhan, Bozorgmehr, Darab, Dariush (Darius), Esfandiar, Esfandyar, Javid, Faramarz, Farhad, Fariborz, Farshid, Farzad, and Yazdan.

==Surnames==
{{see also|Category:Persian-language surnames|Category:Iranian-language surnames|Surname law}}
Prior to 1919, the people of [[Persia]] ([[Iran]]) did not use surnames. An act of the [[Vosough od-Dowleh]] government in 1919 [[Surname law|introduced the use of surnames]],<ref>احمد کسروی، تاریخ 18 سالۀ آذربایجان</ref> and the practice expanded during the reign of [[Reza Shah]] (r. 1925–1941). Prior to that, a person was often distinguished from others by a combination of prefixes and suffixes attached to his or her name. If it was omitted, that person might be taken for someone else.<ref>{{cite book |author=Salmani, Ustad Muhammad-`Aliy-i, the Barber |others=Gail, Marizieh (trans.) |title=My Memories of Bahá'u'lláh |publisher=Kalimát Press |year=1982 |location=Los Angeles, USA |isbn=0-933770-21-9 |page=123 }}</ref> Since the adoption of surnames, [[Ahmadi (surname)|Ahmadi]] has become the most popular surname in Iran.<ref>[http://forebears.co.uk/iran#surnames Surnames Found in Iran]</ref>

In many cases individuals were known by the name of the district, city, town, or even the village from which they came by using the locality's name as a suffix, for example: Nuri, [[Khorasan Province|Khorasani]], [[Māzandarān Province|Mazandarani]], [[Kordestan]]i, [[Tehran]]i, [[Esfahān|Esfahani]], [[Gilani (disambiguation)|Gilani]], [[Hamedan]]i, and [[Shiraz]]i. The same rule is followed for the many millions of Iranians who have surnames of regions or cities of the [[Caucasus]] region. The latter was forcefully ceded in the course of the 19th century to [[Imperial Russia]] through the [[Treaty of Gulistan]] (1813) and [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] (1828). Examples of common [[Iran|Iranian]] surnames in this regard are [[Dagestan|Daghestan]]i, [[Karabagh|Gharabaghi]], [[Derbent|Darbandi]], [[Shirvan]]i, [[Yerevan|Iravani]], [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic|Nakhjevani]], [[Lankaran|Lankarani]]. 

Among many other secularization and modernization reforms, surnames were required by Reza Shah, following similar contemporary patterns in [[Turkey]] under [[Mustafa Kemal Atatürk]], and later in [[Egypt]] under [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tehranian |first=Majid |title=Disenchanted Worlds: Secularization and Democratization in the Middle East |journal=Paper for Presentation at the World Congress of International Political Science Association |date=August 1–5, 2000 |url=http://www2.hawaii.edu/~majid/draft_papers/secularization/secularization.html |accessdate=2006-09-28 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060912101324/http://www2.hawaii.edu/~majid/draft_papers/secularization/secularization.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-09-12}}</ref>

